com.bugsnag.android

Interface Delivery


  • public interface Delivery
    Implementations of this interface deliver Error Reports and Sessions captured to the Bugsnag API.

    A default Delivery implementation is provided as part of Bugsnag initialization, but you may wish to use your own implementation if you have requirements such as pinning SSL certificates, for example.

    Any custom implementation must be capable of sending Error Reports and Sessions as documented at https://docs.bugsnag.com/api/

    See Also:
    DefaultDelivery

    • Method Detail

      • deliver

        void deliver(SessionTrackingPayload payload,
             Configuration config)
      throws DeliveryFailureException
        Posts an array of sessions to the Bugsnag Session Tracking API.

        This request must be delivered to the endpoint at Configuration.getSessionEndpoint(), and contain the HTTP headers from Configuration.getSessionApiHeaders().

        If the request was not successful and you wish to try again later, throw DeliveryFailureException. The notifier will cache the payload and initiate delivery at a future time. For example, if you are unable to obtain a network connection, it would make sense to attempt delivery later on, whereas if the status code was 400, it would not.

        See https://docs.bugsnag.com/api/sessions/

        Parameters:
        payload - The session tracking payload
        config - The configuration by which this request will be sent
        Throws:
        DeliveryFailureException - when delivery is not successful and the report should be stored for future attempts.

        Posts an Error Report to the Bugsnag Error Reporting API.

        This request must be delivered to the endpoint at Configuration.getSessionEndpoint(), and contain the HTTP headers from Configuration.getSessionApiHeaders().

        If the request was not successful and you wish to try again later, throw DeliveryFailureException. The notifier will cache the payload and initiate delivery at a future time. For example, if you are unable to obtain a network connection, it would make sense to attempt delivery later on, whereas if the status code was 400, it would not.

        See https://docs.bugsnag.com/api/error-reporting/
